reviews.review_text: This is one of my favorite auds on the Archive, Thanksgiving Dead on Campus.  Bails of love washing up all over the place.  The band smokes this show,  Well worth a dl.

One of the best Aud's By far, one of the best Aud recording I've ever come across. Fantastic Shakedown>Franklin's>Estimated...clearly a regroovinated time for the band with Brent aboard.  5+ for the recording!!!
Tasty Aud and show to boot... The second set on here simply smokes. This aud is very good quality also, which makes it that much more enjoyable. Get this one now and blast it!!!

I was there Final semester of law school at UF, sitting (well, standing) 5 rows from stage. Took a great b & w photo of Garcia and Weir, printed it in Journalism College dark room.  29 yrs later my brother finds our ticket stubs!  Got the pic and stub framed. Excellent show, and phenomenal recording. Go Gators!
I Was There It was the gym.  I remember people saying the GD show was going to be the last event there.

I've Been There Alligator Alley/Florida Gym was not torn down and is still utilized today. For any seekers, it is on the opposite side of the football stadium than the O'Connell Center, adjoining the swimming pool. Go Gators!
Nice We can download this!? Holy $h!t. Awesome. Great show.

This Seminoles Loves Alligator Alley! Nov 29, 2014....On this college football rivalry Saturday, The Florida Gators will travel to Tallahassee to play the Florida State Seminoles, my alma mater. I always get a little nostalgic on this particular Saturday each year, so I thought I would take a little trip down memory lane. 

On 11/29/80, I was 16 years old and a Junior in high school living in Jacksonville, FL about 75 miles from Gainesville. I had never heard of the Grateful Dead so this show was completely off of my radar. I had just seen AC/DC Back in Black Tour and was getting ready for Rossington-Collins Band in Jax on Jan. 3, 1981...growing up in Jax, it was all about Lynyrd Skynyrd and southern rock. This show is at the top of my "shoulda woulda coulda" been at Grateful Dead shows from the early-mid 1980s. The first set is chock full of well played material of that era, and the Shakedown>Franklin's 2nd set opener is a jammed out, one of a kind segue sequence spectacular! 

This show and this source have long been one of my all-time favorite audience recordings. My only question is, how far apart were the mics because the mix is perfect?! 

My compliments to Bob Wagner, Jim Wise, Charlie Miller and anyone else involved with this incredible FOB sweet spot sensation! I also must tip my cap to the Oade Brothers from Thomasville, GA and their contributions to taping technological advances. 

From a latter day Grateful taper to the pioneers of taping, thank you gentlemen for creating near perfection with this gem! Go Seminoles!   

Tim Cox FSU, Class of 1986
Great audience recording One of the best audience recordings I have downloaded or heard. Clear vocals, sharp instruments, great set list, great form. Highly reccomend.

Energy Driven Masterpiece! This show has been near the top of my list for many years. I recently settled in for the long drive over the Sonora Pass and put this show on to keep me company. I'd forgotten how damn good this one is, and the audience recording only makes it better. The real magic here is in the music, but the band is clearly driven by the feedback of this raucous crowd, and this recording captures it perfectly. The crowd never gives in, and the band never gives up. Amazing till the last note. "It couldn't happen to a nicer team" - bobby!

(night after) 15th Trip Around the Sun Some people aren't too keen on this first set, but I love it. Maybe it's the Floridian in me, I don't know. Maybe it's Bobby getting sexy with the "Gainesville girls," who knows? Or maybe just that sweet 80' sound. At any rate, while it's well-played enough, I agree with the reviewers' sentiment that it's nothing spectacular, probably even semi-forgetful. Second set, though: look out! It's a power-house. Strong versions of everything, here, and non-stop. Mellows for a bit with He's Gone and there's some tender, quiet moments during the Stella Blue, coming out from the wonderful chaos of post-Space/Other One. Masterful AUD recording, Casey Jones encore, this was a fun one in the swamp, no doubt.

First Dead Show!  This was my first Dead Show!  I was with some Great DeadHead friends, packed in like sardines against the front door of the Florida Gym.   We were all smuggling some part of the Taping Rig we were going to put together once we got inside.  It was general admission, so it was a race to get to the best seats possible for taping!   I had already been listening to bootlegs, and albums for a couple of years, so much of the music was already familiar, it I was just blown away.  The acid helped!  Shout out to the OadeBros, and the Athens Hog Mountain Crew (you know who you are!)  WilliamJ.
